BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kometa-fellows-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T211726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Kometa Fellows 2026: Field Journalism\, Photography\, and
  Writing
DESCRIPTION:Kometa\, a French literary and journalism magazine\, awards fel
 lowships to journalists\, writers\, and photographers documenting reality 
 in contexts of war\, censorship\, or severe social and political tensions.
  Projects must be rooted in direct field experience and focused on contemp
 orary rather than historical events. Projects already under a contractual 
 agreement are ineligible. AMOUNT: €10\,000 per Fellow\, six Fellows sele
 cted. WHAT FELLOWS RECEIVE: one year of funding\; publication of the compl
 eted project (partial or full) in Kometa\; opportunity to contribute to th
 e monthly newsletter\; mentorship through editorial collaboration. 2026 FO
 CUS AREAS: disinformation and narrative wars\; political and social change
 s in the Gulf. DEADLINE: 31 July 2026. APPLY via the Tally form (https://t
 ally.so/r/J9XxMK)\, in French or English (about 30 to 45 minutes). Contact
 : fellows@kometarevue.com.\n\nOrganisation: Kometa (French literary and jo
 urnalism magazine)\nLocation: Remote / field-based (international)\nAward:
  €10\,000 per Fellow\, six Fellows selected. No application fee.\nDurati
 on: One year of funding for field work and research\n\nMore: https://komet
 arevue.com/page/fellows?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
URL:https://kometarevue.com/page/fellows?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote / field-based (international)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:longview-digital-minds-grants-applied-work-2026@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T211726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: Longview Philanthropy: Digital Minds Grants for Applied W
 ork 2026
DESCRIPTION:Longview Philanthropy invites proposals for applied work on the
  potential consciousness\, sentience\, moral status\, or experiences of AI
  systems. Typical grants are $50\,000–$2\,000\,000 per project\, with pr
 oposals outside that range considered when justified. New organisations ma
 y also receive some operational support. ELIGIBLE ACTIVITIES: seed funding
  for new organisations (think tanks\, research bodies\, initiatives)\; men
 torship programmes for researchers entering the digital minds field\; inte
 rnships\, new hires\, or focused programmes on digital minds at existing A
 I organisations\, academic labs\, or policy institutions\; convenings and 
 field-building (workshops\, conferences\, summits\, working groups address
 ing technical and governance questions). AREAS OF INTEREST: measuring AI w
 elfare\; consciousness and sentience research\; governance and legal/socia
 l science frameworks for potentially sentient AI\; communications work for
  thoughtful public discourse\; research beyond the US\; support organisati
 ons and operations professionals for independent technical researchers. SE
 LECTION CRITERIA: potential impact\, track record\, demonstrated interest 
 in digital minds and its relationship to AI risk\, cost-effectiveness\, le
 gal compliance. Deadline: 10 July 2026. Questions: digitalminds-rfp@longvi
 ew.org. Apply at https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-a
 nd-applied-work-on-digital-minds/.\n\nOrganisation: Longview Philanthropy\
 nLocation: Worldwide / remote (grant-eligible countries listed in applicat
 ion form)\nAward: Typical grants $50\,000–$2\,000\,000 per project\; pro
 posals outside this range considered when the work justifies it. May inclu
 de some operational support for new organisations. No application fee.\nDu
 ration: Project-based\; duration varies by scope.\n\nMore: https://www.lon
 gview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-work-on-digital-minds
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-wor
 k-on-digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
LOCATION:Worldwide / remote (grant-eligible countries listed in application
  form)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:longview-digital-minds-research-fellowships-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T211726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: Longview Philanthropy: Digital Minds Research Fellowships
  2026
DESCRIPTION:Longview Philanthropy Research Fellowships support scholars pur
 suing research on the potential consciousness\, sentience\, moral status\,
  and legal position of AI systems. AMOUNT: $55\,000–$120\,000/year (thro
 ugh a university\, with 10% research budget and standard fringe benefits)\
 , or $80\,000–$150\,000/year (direct stipend\, with suggested 5–10% al
 location for research and travel). Compute resources available for machine
  learning research. Invitation and funding to attend the annual Center for
  Mind\, Ethics\, and Policy Summit at NYU. ELIGIBILITY: must have or be ex
 pected to receive a doctoral degree in computer science\, neuroscience\, a
  related technical discipline\, law\, medicine\, or applied social science
  by September 2027 or fellowship start date (exceptions for equivalent res
 earch experience)\; fellows arrange their own institutional affiliation\; 
 fellowship may be conditional on institutional affiliation or attendance a
 t events. SELECTION CRITERIA: demonstrated interest in digital minds and i
 ts relation to AI risk\; evidence of research promise (publications\, acad
 emic achievements\, references). DURATION: 1–2 years\; second year condi
 tional on ongoing programme requirements. AREAS OF INTEREST: introspection
 \, welfare measurement\, interpretability\, model character\, correlates o
 f consciousness\, valence research\, governance frameworks\, legal and pol
 itical responses to potentially sentient AI. Deadline: 10 July 2026. Requi
 red application materials: CV\, description of possible research direction
 s (~1\,000 words)\, intended outcomes\, what you would do without this fel
 lowship (~150–400 words)\, career goals (~300 words). Questions: digital
 minds-rfp@longview.org. Apply at https://www.longview.org/request-for-prop
 osals-research-and-applied-work-on-digital-minds/.\n\nOrganisation: Longvi
 ew Philanthropy\nLocation: Worldwide / remote or institutional (grant-elig
 ible countries listed in application form)\nAward: $55\,000–$120\,000/ye
 ar through a university\, or $80\,000–$150\,000/year direct stipend\; pl
 us research budget (10% of salary)\, conference travel\, and compute resou
 rces where applicable. No application fee.\nDuration: 1–2 years. Second 
 year conditional on continuing to meet programme requirements.\n\nMore: ht
 tps://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-work-on-
 digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-wor
 k-on-digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
LOCATION:Worldwide / remote or institutional (grant-eligible countries list
 ed in application form)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:revitalizing-rituals-2026-open-call@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T211726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260719
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260720
SUMMARY:Deadline: Revitalizing Rituals 2026 Open Call
DESCRIPTION:Revitalizing Rituals invites artists from all disciplines -- so
 und\, movement\, visual arts\, installation\, performance\, and transdisci
 plinary practices -- to join a research-creation journey across two landsc
 apes: Bhar Lazreg in Tunisia and the wetlands of Somogy County in Hungary.
  The project explores rituals as living forms of belonging: reconnecting c
 ommunities\, land\, memory\, food\, ecological reciprocity\, and the more-
 than-human world. Selected artists work with local communities as co-parti
 cipants in a shared inquiry into moving from extraction toward reciprocity
 . Organised by Homo Faber Alapítvány (Hungary). AMOUNT: EUR 6\,000 gross
  artist fee and production budget\; international travel and per diems cov
 ered\; on-site accommodation provided. ELIGIBILITY: minimum 5 years of act
 ive artistic practice\; portfolio reflecting interest in situated or relat
 ional work\; no formal degree required\; working language is English (loca
 l language navigation valued)\; must be available for the full residency c
 ycle including all international travel\; must be able to legally receive 
 the fee and invoice the organising partners from country of residence. Str
 ongly encourages applications from historically marginalised or underrepre
 sented voices. KEY DATES: Application Deadline 19 July 2026 (midnight) -- 
 note the open call PDF also references a 5 July date\; the officially prom
 oted deadline is 19 July\; Online Q&A 29 June 2026\, 14:00 Tunisia / 15:00
  CET (register at https://forms.gle/brnZvXvFe4JB8zL26)\; Online Conversati
 ons with shortlisted artists: mid July to mid August 2026\; Selection Resu
 lts: 31 August 2026\; Placemaking Camp: 1 week\, end of November 2026\, Hu
 ngary\; Storytellers Camp: 1 week\, March 2027\, Tunisia\; Residency Perio
 d: minimum 1 month (splittable)\, April to July 2027\; Final Presentation:
  August 2027\; Closing Event: 3 days\, winter/early spring 2028\, Hungary.
  Apply via the open call form linked at https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/up
 loads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Homo Faber Alapítvány (Homo Faber Foundation)\nLocation: Bhar Lazreg\, T
